    {
      "id": "RQ-0006",
      "status": "done",
      "title": "Use pi session cwd instead of process.cwd where available",
      "priority": "low",
      "tags": [
        "pi-extension",
        "cwd",
        "lifecycle"
      ],
      "scope": [
        "src/cursor-native-tool-display.ts",
        "src/cursor-provider.ts",
        "test/cursor-provider.test.ts"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "src/cursor-native-tool-display.ts:119-133 registers native replay tools using process.cwd() despite receiving ExtensionContext.",
        "src/cursor-provider.ts:573-582 passes process.cwd() to Cursor Agent.create local cwd.",
        "Installed pi extension docs expose ctx.cwd as the session working directory."
      ],
      "plan": [
        "Replace process.cwd() with ctx.cwd for native tool replay registration.",
        "Investigate whether provider stream context/options expose session cwd; if not, document limitation or upstream a pi provider option.",
        "Add/update tests for non-default cwd where feasible.",
        "Run npm test and npm run typecheck."
      ],
      "notes": [
        "Started by agent to use pi session cwd where available.",
        "Native Cursor tool replay now registers wrapped read/bash/ls tools with ExtensionContext.cwd instead of process.cwd. Provider streamCursor remains on process.cwd because pi-ai Context/SimpleStreamOptions do not expose session cwd; documented in code and added follow-up RQ-0009. Added test proving native read resolves relative paths against session cwd. Validated with npm test -- test/index.test.ts, npm test, npm run typecheck. Reviewer subagent reported no material findings after RQ-0009 follow-up."
      ],
